{"id":"1806.08625","submitter":"Wilbur Shirley","authors":"Wilbur Shirley, Kevin Slagle, and Xie Chen","title":"Fractional excitations in foliated fracton phases","comments":"40 pages, 24 figures","journal-ref":"Annals of Physics, Volume 410, 167922 (2019)","doi":"10.1016/j.aop.2019.167922","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Fractional excitations in fracton models exhibit novel features not present\nin conventional topological phases: their mobility is constrained, there are an\ninfinitude of types, and they bear an exotic sense of 'braiding'. Hence, they\nrequire a new framework for proper characterization. Based on our definition of\nfoliated fracton phases in which equivalence between models includes the\npossibility of adding layers of gapped 2D states, we propose to characterize\nfractional excitations in these phases up to the addition of quasiparticles\nwith 2D mobility. That is, two quasiparticles differing by a set of\nquasiparticles that move along 2D planes are considered to be equivalent;\nlikewise, 'braiding' statistics are measured in a way that is insensitive to\nthe attachment of 2D quasiparticles. The fractional excitation types and\nstatistics defined in this way provide a universal characterization of the\nunderlying foliated fracton order which can subsequently be used to establish\nphase relations. We demonstrate as an example the equivalence between the\nX-cube model and the semionic X-cube model both in terms of fractional\nexcitations and through an exact mapping.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 22 Jun 2018 12:24:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-24"}
